Title: IPP-Get-Printer-Attributes response  :Verify Absence of Unsupported IPP Attributes
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > N/W Printing > IPP
Steps (Expected Result):
Unsupported IPP attributes should not be present in the response.
Check for the constraint for media size and borderless.
Refer individual product specification
Steps (Step):
Send an IPP Get-Printer-Attributes request to the printer.
Capture the response.
Verify that unsupported IPP attributes (e.g., attributes not defined in the IPP specification or not supported by the printer) are not present in the response.
Note: As PSA driver uses IPP Protocol, using PSA driver need to check IPP printer attributes.
1.Install HP PSA Driver 
2.Once printer is installed using HPPSA, launch Printer properties navigating to printers an faxes 
3.Set settings borderless against  media size

Title: Ensure that the printer can handle multiple large print jobs alternately from both iOS and Android devices without any issues.

Repeat steps 1-4 for multiple print jobs.
Monitor the printer for successful completion of all print jobs.
Note:Test for image aswell as doccument

Title: Verify basic printing after host name change
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > N/W Printing > Airprint
Steps (Expected Result):
1. The service name should be discovered.
All jobs should print with no overlap or blank pages between.
2. Printer's EWS should open successfully without throwing any error messages.
3. Print job should be successful.
Steps (Step):
1. Highlight the configured printer within the print center.
Click Utility window.
On the Network Settings page, change the Host Name to a new value.
Apply settings and exit browser.
Make sure the desired printer is set as default on the client.
Fire a print job.
2. Highlight the configured printer within the print center.
Click on Options & Supplies and choose Utility tab.
Select "Show Printer Webpage"
3. Make sure the desired printer is set as default on the client after IP change.
Fire a print job.
Dependencies: Highlighting printer in Print Center GUI

Access printer EWS
Power cycle the printer

Steps (Expected Result): 1. Printer Should Configured with DhcpV6 Address and stateless IPv6 address. Ping should be successful.
Steps (Step):
1. 1)Configure the printer in Auto IP
2)Change IPconfig method from Auto IP to DHCP
3)Once printer get IPv4 after DORA process
4)Receive Router solicitation packet and send router advertisement packet
5)Receive Solicit Packet and Send Advertise Packet
6)Receive Request Packet and Send Reply Packet
7)Checking for Ping Status for Configured IpV6 Address and stateless IPv6 address
8)Change network protocol to IPv4 only
9)Printer should not be configured with DhcpV6 Address and stateless IPv6 address.
10)Change the network protocol back to both ipv4 and ipv6
11)Printer must be configured with DhcpV6 Address and stateless IPv6 address and ping must be successful
Expected Result:
Printer Should Configured with DhcpV6 Address and stateless IPv6 address. Ping should be successful.

Title: Verify that the  printer can get the reserved IP address all the time_RC_6
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > N/W IpConfig > DHCPv6
Steps (Expected Result):
1.  Printer should acquire IPv6 address from the dhcpv6 server. 
2. Printer should acquire reserve IP after successfully reservation in the DHCP.
3. Printer should acquire reserved IP even after doing resotore network defaults.
Steps (Step):
1. Connect to the printer in isolated network  and ensure  routers are providing IPV6  addresses.

2. Reserve an IPv6 address with DUID in the DHCP server for the printer and make sure the printer have acquired reserved IP address.
3. Do a restore network defaults and connect to the DHCP server

Title: Verify device can be  configured with a manual IPv6 address_TC_13
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > N/W IpConfig > DHCPv6
Steps (Expected Result): 1. Printer should connect successfully to the network 2. Device Should be able to configure a valid IPv6 address. 3. ipv6 should get configured and ipv6 address stack list : Network>>Wired/Wireess>>Status:: should not show stateful adddress. 4. EWS page should open with configured manual IPV6 address. 5. Ping should be successful with the manual IPv6 address. 6. Printer should be able to access through SNMP through the manual IPv6 address. 7. Printer installation with manual IPv6 address is successful and print job should be successfully printed.
Steps (Step):
1.  Connect the printer in a network where DHCPV6 server is running.
2) Go to Netowork tab-Wired/Wireless-IPV6 Configuration-Manual Address.
3) Configure manual ipv6 as same  that of stateful address of the printer
4) Configure a valid IPv6 address manually on the device
5) Try to open EWS page using the configured manual IPV6 address.
6) Try to ping the manual IPv6 address
7) Try accessing the printer through SNMP with the manual IPv6 address.
8) Install the printer with the manual IPv6 address and verify by sending a print job/scan job.

Title: Verify that the printer can obtain a basic DHCPv6 IP address  and parameters using DHCPV6 scope_TC_2
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > N/W IpConfig > DHCPv6
Steps (Expected Result):
1. The printer should get a valid DHCPv6 address 
and should retain the IP even after the power cycle.
 
2  Printer should configured with the DNS primary & secondary server, domain search list.
 
 
3. The printer should always acquire parameters from the dhcpv6 scope, after restore network defaults/OOBE reset.
Steps (Step):
1 Connect to the printer in isolated network having DHCPv6 server and ensure routers are providing IPV6 addresses.
2 Verify if the printer gets a DHCPv6 address.
3 Power cycle and verify the printer status.
4. Configure the DHCPV6 scope with DNS primary & secondary server (Option 23), domain search list (Option 24).
5. Verify same provided information is shown in the EWS page>>Network>>Wired/Wireless Status Information 
6.Restore network defaults/Full  reset the printer and verify the configurations of the printer.

Note: Steps for Full Reset:
1. Hold the power botton of the printer and remove the power cable, after 10 sec. connect the power cable,wait for 5sec and release the power button of the printer->On front panel do home-back-home home->Select Menu-next...-> OOBreset->OK
Dependencies: Restore network defaults/Full  reset the printer

Title: The purpose of this test is to verify the events on various conditions.
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > Eventing > Print_Eventing Manual
Steps (Expected Result):
1. 1.The printer should print the job from client 2 successfully 2.Appropriate error message should be seen on the spooler.
2. 1.Appropriate events should be sent out by the printer for the generated conditions.
3. Events should be received after changing the hostname.
4. 1.When WSDiscovery is enabled back ,the printer status should be shown as 'Ready' and appropriate error message should be seen on the spooler.
5. 1.When WSPrint is enabled back ,the printer status should be shown as 'Ready' and appropriate error message should be seen on the spooler.
6. 1.Appropriate error messages should be seen on spooler irrespective of the configuration method selected.
7. 1.Appropriate error messages should be seen on spooler irrespective of the network connectivity mode.
8. 1.Printer should get discovered irrespective of event condition.
9. 1.Printer should be online and should be able to generate events after the initial 
subscription time of 1 hour is completed.
10. 1.When the client comes to ready state the printer status should be updated appropriately based on printer condition.
11. 1.Printer should come to ready state and appropriate error message should be seen on the spooler.
12. Printer should come back to ready state and events should be sent normally.
13. Printer should have only IPV4 address and appropriate error message should be seen on the spooler and same should be captured in wireshark.
14. Irrespective of the network protocol, appropriate error message should be seen on spooler.???
15. 1.On re-connecting network,printer should come online and appropriate error message should be shown on the spooler.
Steps (Step):
1. 1.Install printer in 2 clients 2.Shutdown client 1 3.Generate an error condition.
Expected Result:
1.The printer should print the job from client 2 successfully 2.Appropriate error message should be seen on the spooler.
2. 1.Install printer  and capture the wireshark traces.  
2.Generate the following alerts  and verify the events 
-Job Canceled at client
-Job Canceled at device 
-Pause printer 
-Online\Offline State
Expected Result:
1.Appropriate events should be sent out by the printer for the generated conditions.
3. 1.Install printer 2.From EWS page, change the Host Name.Wait for 2min. 3.Create an error condition
Expected Result:
Events should be received after changing the hostname.
4. 1.Install printer 2.Disable WSDiscovery.Wait for 30sec. 3.Enable back WSDiscovery.Wait for 30sec. 4.Generate error conditions
Expected Result:
1.When WSDiscovery is enabled back ,the printer status should be shown as 'Ready' and appropriate error message should be seen on the spooler.
5. 1.Install printer 2.Disable WSPrint.Wait for 30sec. 3.Enable back WSPrint.Wait for 30sec. 4.Generate error conditions
Expected Result:
1.When WSPrint is enabled back ,the printer status should be shown as 'Ready' and appropriate error message should be seen on the spooler.
6. 1.Install printer 2.From EWS page change the configuration method from DHCP to Manual.Wait for 5min???????????????
Expected Result:
1.Appropriate error messages should be seen on spooler irrespective of the configuration method selected.
7. 1.Install printer in 1 of the connectivity mode and print test page 2.Now switch the connectivity mode of the printer??? and wait for 5min 3.Generate any error conditions??? 4.Again connect back to the previous connectivity mode.Wait for 5min. 5.Generate any error condition
Expected Result:
1.Appropriate error messages should be seen on spooler irrespective of the network connectivity mode.
8. 1.Install??? printer 2.Generate an event 3.Open Network folder to discover the printer
Expected Result:
1.Printer should get discovered irrespective of event condition.
9. 1.Install printer 2.Leave the printer idle for two hours and give a print job 3.Generate an event condition
Expected Result:
1.Printer should be online and should be able to generate events after the initial 
subscription time of 1 hour is completed.
10. 1.Install??? printer 2.Put the??? client to sleep mode and wait for 2 min 3.Bring back the client to ready state and wait for 10min. 4.Generate any error condition.
Expected Result:
1.When the client comes to ready state the printer status should be updated appropriately based on printer condition.
11. 1.Install??? printer 2.Power off the client 3.Generate an error condition 4.Power on the client and wait for 10min.
Expected Result:
1.Printer should come to ready state and appropriate error message should be seen on the spooler.
12. 1.Install??? printer 2.Power off the printer after installation 3.Power on the printer and generate an error condition and check for the events
Expected Result:
Printer should come back to ready state and events should be sent normally.
13. 1.Install printer and start wireshark capture. 2.Open EWS page-->Network-->Network Identification-->Network protocols-->Enable only IPV4.Wait for 2 min ans generate error condition.
Expected Result:
Printer should have only IPV4 address and appropriate error message should be seen on the spooler and same should be captured in wireshark.
14. 1.Install printer 2.Open EWS page-->Network-->Network Identification-->Network protocols-->Enable only IPV6.Wait for 2 min and generate error condition.
Expected Result:
Irrespective of the network protocol, appropriate error message should be seen on spooler.???
15. 1.Install the printer. 2.Disconnect the printer.Wait for 1min. 3.Re-connect the network.Generate an error condition.
Expected Result:
1.On re-connecting network,printer should come online and appropriate error message should be shown on the spooler.

Title: Verify the TLS protocol version OID through SNMP
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > N/W Security > TLS
Steps (Expected Result):
1. Peforming walk operation on the OID npSecuritySSLProtocol(1.3.6.1.4.1.11.2.4.3.20.58.0) should successfully return the current TLS protocol version selected in the printer.
Note: the values for TLS1.2, TLS1.1 and TLS1.0 are 8, 4 and 2 respectively . Selection of multiple protocol selections shall be made by adding their values and performing the SET operation.
2. 1.Performing SET operation should be successful. 
2.Set value 10 should enable TLS1.2 and TLS1.0.
3. 1.Performing GET operation should return the value as 10 .
2.returned value 10 should be understood as value of TLS1.2(8) and Value of TLS1.0(2) is added and returned.
4. Any combination of TLS protocol selection should be successful and SET and GET operations should be successful and printer should be accessible through SNMP.
Steps (Step):
1. Pre requisite:Pre requisite: Make sure MIB browser is installed in the test machine and the printer is connected to a valid network and accessible through SNMP, enable the write permissions through EWS page.

Perform walk on the OID 
npSecuritySSLProtocol(1.3.6.1.4.1.11.2.4.3.20.58.0)
Expected Result:
Peforming walk operation on the OID npSecuritySSLProtocol(1.3.6.1.4.1.11.2.4.3.20.58.0) should successfully return the current TLS protocol version selected in the printer.
Note: the values for TLS1.2, TLS1.1 and TLS1.0 are 8, 4 and 2 respectively . Selection of multiple protocol selections shall be made by adding their values and performing the SET operation.
2. Pre requisite: Keep all the ciphers listed in EWS are selected in the printer.

Perform SET operation for the multiple protocol selection on npSecuritySSLProtocol(1.3.6.1.4.1.11.2.4.3.20.58.0)  . SET TLS1.2 and TLS1.0 using SNMP. Value to be set should be 10 (value of TLS1.2 is 8 added with value of TLS1.0 is 2).
Expected Result:
1.Performing SET operation should be successful. 
2.Set value 10 should enable TLS1.2 and TLS1.0.
3. Pre requisite: Keep all the ciphers listed are selected in the printer.

Perform GET operation for the OID npSecuritySSLProtocol (1.3.6.1.4.1.11.2.4.3.20.58.0) and verify the printer behavior
Expected Result:
1.Performing GET operation should return the value as 10 .
2.returned value 10 should be understood as value of TLS1.2(8) and Value of TLS1.0(2) is added and returned.
4. Pre requisite: Keep all the ciphers listed are selected in the printer.

Perform possible combinations of multiple protocol selection with their values added and perform SET and GET operation.
Expected Result:
Any combination of TLS protocol selection should be successful and SET and GET operations should be successful and printer should be accessible through SNMP.

Title: Test is to Check Events Logged When ID Certificate is Installed Multiple Times
PreConditions:
1.The device is powered on and connected to the network.
2.Access to the device's Embedded Web Server (EWS) and Front Panel User Interface (FPUI).
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > N/W Security > EU RED
Steps (Expected Result):
1.The ID certificate should be installed successfully each time it is uploaded.
2.An event should be logged in the event log for each installation of the ID certificate, indicating that the certificate has been installed multiple times.
3.The privacy log report should contain entries for each installation of the ID certificate.
4.The privacy log report should be accessible and downloadable/printable from both the EWS and FPUI.
Steps (Step):
1.Access the Printer's Web Interface:

Open a web browser and navigate to the printer's web interface or management console.
Log in with administrative credentials.
2.Navigate to Certificate Management:

Go to the certificate management section.
3.Install the ID Certificate for the First Time:

Select the option to install a new ID certificate.
Upload the ID certificate file.
Enter any required information (e.g., password if needed).
Save the changes.
4.Check Event Log for First Installation:

Navigate to the event log section.
Verify that an event is logged indicating the ID certificate change.
5.Install the Same ID Certificate Again:

Go back to the certificate management section.
Select the option to install a new ID certificate.
Upload the same ID certificate file again.
Enter any required information (e.g., password if needed).
Save the changes.
6.Check Event Log for Second Installation:

Navigate to the event log section.
Verify that an event is logged indicating the second installation of the same ID certificate.
7.Repeat the Installation Process:

Repeat the installation process for the ID certificate multiple times (e.g., three or more times).
Each time, upload the same ID certificate file and save the changes.
8.Check Event Log for Each Installation:

After each installation, navigate to the event log section.
Verify that an event is logged for each installation of the ID certificate.
9.Access Privacy Logs on EWS:

Go to the menu Support Tools > Reports and Pages.
In the ???Print?? or ???Download?? tabs, select the ???Privacy Log??.
Download or print the privacy log report.
10.Access Privacy Logs on FPUI:

On the printer's front panel UI, navigate to Menu -> Settings -> Tools -> Status Reports -> Print #Privacy Log.
Print the privacy log report.
11.Validate Privacy Logs:

Review the downloaded or printed privacy log report.
Check for entries indicating the multiple installations of the ID certificate

Title: Test is to Check for multiple events happening together and all are logged (certificate change, factory reset, network reset, security reset)
PreConditions:
1.The device is powered on and connected to the network.
2.Access to the device's Embedded Web Server (EWS) and Front Panel User Interface (FPUI).
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > N/W Security > EU RED
Steps (Expected Result):
1.The ID certificate should be installed successfully, and an event should be logged indicating the change.
2.The self-signed certificate should be generated successfully, and an event should be logged indicating the change.
3.The CA certificate should be installed successfully, and an event should be logged indicating the change.
4.The CSR should be generated successfully, and an event should be logged indicating the generation.
5.The network reset should be performed successfully, and an event should be logged indicating the reset.
6.The factory reset (RFD) should be performed successfully, and an event should be logged indicating the reset.
7.The security reset should be performed successfully, and an event should be logged indicating the reset.
8.The privacy log report should contain entries for the changes made to the ID certificate, self-signed certificate, CA certificate, CSR generation, network reset, factory reset, and security reset.
9.The privacy log report should be accessible and downloadable/printable from both the EWS and FPUI.
Steps (Step):
1.Access the Printer's Web Interface:

Open a web browser and navigate to the printer's web interface or management console.
Log in with administrative credentials.
2.Navigate to Certificate Management:

Go to the certificate management section.
3.Change the ID Certificate:

Select the option to install a new ID certificate.
Upload the ID certificate file.
Enter any required information (e.g., password if needed).
Save the changes.
4.Generate a New Self-Signed Certificate:

Select the option to generate a new self-signed certificate.
Enter the required details and key length.
Save the changes.
5.Change the CA Certificate:

Select the option to install a new CA certificate.
Upload the CA certificate file.
Save the changes.
6.Generate a CSR:

Select the option to generate a Certificate Signing Request (CSR).
Enter the required details and key length.
Save the CSR.
7.Perform a Network Reset:

Navigate to the network settings section.
Select the option to reset network settings.
Confirm the reset.
8.Perform a Factory Reset (RFD):

Navigate to the settings section.
Select the option to restore factory defaults (RFD).
Confirm the reset.
9.Perform a Security Reset:

Navigate to the security settings section.
Select the option to reset security settings.
Confirm the reset.
10.Access Privacy Logs on EWS:

Go to the menu Support Tools > Reports and Pages.
In the ???Print?? or ???Download?? tabs, select the ???Privacy Log??.
Download or print the privacy log report.
11.Access Privacy Logs on FPUI:

On the printer's front panel UI, navigate to Menu -> Settings -> Tools -> Status Reports -> Print #Privacy Log.
Print the privacy log report.
12.Validate Privacy Logs:

Review the downloaded or printed privacy log report.
Check for entries indicating the changes made to the ID certificate, self-signed certificate, CA certificate, and CSR generation.
Check for entries indicating the network reset, factory reset, and security reset.

Title: Test is to Check for Network Reset, RFD,  from UI and EWS on Printers
PreConditions:
1.The device is powered on and connected to the network.
2.Access to the device's Embedded Web Server (EWS) and Front Panel User Interface (FPUI).
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > N/W Security > EU RED
Steps (Expected Result):
1.Network Reset:

The network reset should be performed successfully.
The printer's network settings should be reset to default values.
The printer should reconnect to the network with default network settings.
An event should be logged indicating the network reset.
Network reset should not clear the previous privacy logs


2.Factory Reset (RFD):

The factory reset should be performed successfully.
The printer's settings should be reset to factory defaults.
The printer should reboot and be operational with default settings.
An event should be logged indicating the factory reset.
Factory reset should clear the previous privacy logs 
3.Privacy Logs:

The privacy log report should contain entries for the network reset, factory reset.
The privacy log report should be accessible and downloadable/printable from both the EWS and FPUI.
Steps (Step):
1.Access the Printer's Web Interface:
Open a web browser and navigate to the printer's web interface or management console.
Log in with administrative credentials.

2.Perform a Network Reset from UI  and EWS:
Navigate to the network settings section.
Select the option to reset network settings.
Confirm the reset.
Wait for the printer to complete the network reset and reconnect to the network.

3.Verify Network Reset:
Check the printer's network settings to ensure they have been reset to default values.
Verify that the printer has reconnected to the network with default network settings.

4.Perform a Factory Reset (RFD) From UI and EWS:
Navigate to the settings section.
Select the option to restore factory defaults (RFD).
Confirm the reset.
Wait for the printer to complete the factory reset and reboot.

5.Verify Factory Reset:
Check the printer's settings to ensure they have been reset to factory defaults.
Verify that the printer is operational with default settings.

6.Access Privacy Logs on EWS:
Go to the menu Support Tools > Reports and Pages.
In the Print or Download tabs, select the Privacy Log.
Download or print the privacy log report.

7.Access Privacy Logs on FPUI:
On the printer's front panel UI, navigate to Menu -> Settings -> Tools -> Status Reports -> Print #Privacy Log.
Print the privacy log report.

8.Validate Privacy Logs:
Review the downloaded or printed privacy log report.
Check for entries indicating the network reset, factory reset,

Title: 01 Network Consistency
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > Sleep/Idle
Steps (Expected Result):
1. Able to get valid IP.
2. EWS is accessible.
Able to set new hostname.
Able to set new bonjour name.
Able to disable advanced setting option.
Able to connect wireless successfully with valid IP address.
1. Able to print network config page.
2. Settings that have been changed previously is reflected on the Network Config Page.
3.Able to flash successfully.
Able to connect wireless successfully with valid IP address.
Hostname is retained as per previously changed.
Bonjour name is retained as per previously changed.
Advanced settings are retained as per previously changed.
Network Config Page showing correct settings as per previously set.
Steps (Step):
Steps:
1. Connect printer to network via wired and get valid IP.
2. Enter printer's EWS.
Steps:
1. Go to Network -> General -> Network Identification.
2. Change printer's hostname and fill up to its max hostname.
3. Select Apply.
Steps:
1. Go to Network -> IPv4 -> Advanced Settings-> Bonjour.
2. Change the printer's bonjour name to any 63 char name.
3. Select Apply.
Steps:
1. Go to Network -> IPv4 -> Advanced Settings.
2. Disable any options available ( IPP / SLP / WINS / LLMNR )
3. Select Apply.
Steps:
1. Unplug LAN cable from printer.
2. rom Front Panel, go to Setup->Network->Wireless Setup Wizard.
3. Connect to any wireless setup.
Steps:
1. Print network config page.
2. Flash printer via the method stated above.
Steps:
After flashing, Check that printer power cycles and is able to connect wireless
Steps:
1. Go to Network -> IPv4 -> Network Identification
2. Check the hostname.
Steps:
1. Go to Network -> IPv4 -> Advanced Settings-> Bonjour.
2. Check the Bonjour name.
3. Select Apply.
Steps:
1. Go to Network -> IPv4 -> Advanced Settings.
2. Disable any options available ( IPP / SLP / WINS / LLMNR )
3. Select Apply.
Steps:
1. Print Network Configuration Page.
2. Check all settings set previously.

Title: Check  printer behavior when running all printer supported protocols simultaneaously.
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > Sleep/Idle
Steps (Expected Result):
1. 1.Printer should be successfully put into paperless mode.
2.When the test is initiated, multiple command prompt windows should be opened for each of the protocol supported by the printer (P9100,WSP,LLMNR,EWS,SLP,WSD etc)
3.Printer should not go to bad state during the test.
Steps (Step):
1. 1.Bring up the printer.
2.Put the printer into paperless mode by running the following command in sift tool  - udws "smgr_pe.multi_button_push 58"
3.On client open the contention file.
4.Enter the ip of the printer.
5.Enter the ip of the client and click enter.
Expected Result:
1.Printer should be successfully put into paperless mode.
2.When the test is initiated, multiple command prompt windows should be opened for each of the protocol supported by the printer (P9100,WSP,LLMNR,EWS,SLP,WSD etc)
3.Printer should not go to bad state during the test.

Screen title: Wireless Details Help
Screen footer: OK
Screen text:

?? IP Address: The printer's numerical address on the network. 
?? Signal: The strength of the wireless signal between the printer and wireless router. (If the signal strength is low, try moving the printer closer to the router.)
?? Network Name: The name of the wireless network to which the printer is connected. 
?? MAC: The printer's name on the network. Also called the "Hardware Address."
?? Host Name: Another name for the printer on the network.
?? Bonjour Name: The name used by Bonjour (mDNS) services. 
?? Subnet Mask: The mechanism used to divide a single IP network into several different networks.
?? Default Gateway: The address of the gateway or router.
?? DNS Server: The name of the Domain Name System used by the printer.

Title: Password by Default
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > Management > EWS > EWS
Steps (Expected Result):
Expected Result:
1.A valid IP address can be obtained.
2.The printer's initial PIN number can be found in one of the corresponding places
3.PIN code can be used successfully and login successfully.
4.The default PIN should be display from the printer information page.
5.The default PIN should not be display from the printer status page.
Expected Result:
1.Can be applied successfully.
2.access to fail.
3.access to successful
4.The default PIN should not display from the printer information page.
5.The default PIN should not be display from the printer status page.


Expected Result:
1.Printer restore factory Settings successfully.
2.access to fail.
3.access to successful.
4.The default PIN should still be displayed from the printer information page.
5.The default PIN should not be display from the printer status page.
Expected results:
1.Printer restore network settings should be successful
2.Should be able to access with custom password
3.RND should not reset custom password
Steps (Step):
Step:
1.The printer is connected to a valid wired/wireless network.(Obtained IP: 192.168.103.xx)
2.To log into the EWS page, the pop-up box prompts you to enter a username and password.
3.The default PIN should be accessible from the following locations:
? Printed on a label on the back of the printer
? Printed on the printer information page
? Shown on the control panel (for products with graphical displays)
4.Enter the user name and PIN correctly.
5.Print printer info page and Look at the page for PIN information.
6.Print printer status report.
EWS -> Tools -> Product Information -> Supply Status -> Print Printer Status Report
Look at the page for PIN information.
Step:
1.EWS -> Settings -> Security -> Password Settings
2.Enter the new password and confirm that the password is the same.
3.Apply.
4.Reaccess EWS page & Use the original printer PIN.
5.Reaccess EWS page & Use the new printer password.
6.Print printer info page and Look at the page for PIN information.
(the printer should no longer display the default PIN on internal reports or control panel once the user has changed the administrator password.)
7..Print printer status report.
EWS -> Tools -> Product Information -> Supply Status -> Print Printer Status Report
Look at the page for PIN information.
Step:
1.Restore factory Settings for printer
2.The printer is reconnected to a valid network
Access EWS page.
Log in with the new password that the user changed
3.Re-use the default PIN number to access EWS
4.Print printer info page and Look at the page for PIN information.
5.Print printer status report and Look at the page for PIN information.
Steps:
1.perform RND for printer
2.The printer is reconnected to a valid network then access EWS page with changed password
3.Access EWS with default password

Title: Synchronize with a Network Time Server - Error Handling 01-02
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > Management > EWS > EWS
Steps (Expected Result):
Expected Results:

1. When Apply, printer should reflect the current date / time (GMT+8) which is in sync with the NTP server 

2. After printer power on, printer should still show the old date / time

3. After one more hour (after printer is powered on), printer should syn to latest date / time on EWS and FP. Wireshark should also show packets transmission.
Expected Results:

When Apply, printer should reflect the current date / time (GMT+8) which is in sync with the NTP server

After printer power on, printer should still show the old date / time

After one more hour (after printer is reconnect back to network), printer should syn to latest date / time on EWS and FP. Wireshark should also show packets transmission.
Steps (Step):
Pre-condition/s:

1. Prepare a Windows 2012 server with NTP services turned ON with current date / time set (GMT+8)

2. Ensure printer is in latest FW that has no date / time set yet

3. Ensure printer is connected to the network that has the Win2k12 server



Steps:

1. Browse printer EWS -> Settings -> Preferences -> Date / Time

2. Under Synchronize with a Network Time Server, select Synchronize with a network time server

4. Key in the IP address / hostname of the NTP server

5. Key in 1 hour under "Synchronize Time with Server Every"

6. Select Apply

7. Turn on Wireshark and monitor

8. Turn OFF printer

9. Change NTP server timing to either Ahead or Lagging

10. Wait for more than one hour

11. Turn ON printer, check the printer date / time on EWS and FP.

12. Wait for another one hour, check the printer date / time on EWS and FP.
Pre-condition/s:

Prepare a Windows 2012 server with NTP services turned ON with current date / time set (GMT+8)

Ensure printer is in latest FW that has no date / time set yet

Ensure printer is connected to the network that has the Win2k12 server

Steps:

Browse printer EWS -> Settings -> Preferences -> Date / Time

Under Synchronize with a Network Time Server, select Synchronize with a network time server

Key in the IP address / hostname of the NTP server

Key in 1 hour under "Synchronize Time with Server Every"

Select Apply

Turn on Wireshark and monitor

Disconnect printer from Network

Change NTP server timing to either Ahead or Lagging

Wait for more than one hour

Re-connect printer to network, check the printer date / time on EWS and FP.

Wait for another one hour, check the printer date / time on EWS and FP.

Title: Verify discovery on HP Smart APP when weak signal triggers when printer was not added initially
PreConditions:
1. Printer is not connected to any network (wired/wireless)
2.Keep AP and printer at such distance to simulate weak signal strength.
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > OOBE
Steps (Expected Result):
1. Weak Wifi-Signal should pop up after 30 secs when printer is connected.
2. Printer is able to be discovered on HP Smart APP across all platforms and able to print
Steps (Step):
1. Printer should be in ready state
2. Go to menu>settings>network>wifi>WSW>Start
3. Select an SSID>enter password>submit
4. Check the Wi-Fi connection state and printer has valid IP address 
5. Very Weak Signal strength pop-up comes after 30 secs.
6. Click on Hide.
7. Try to discover printer in windows client on HP Smart App
8. Add printer and give print job.
9. Try to discover printer on Mobile devices on HP smart APP and give print job
Dependencies: HP smart client and Mobile related cannot automate

Title: Test is to set up a printer in AWC and Non-AWC mode using the HP Smart Setup method
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > OOBE
Steps (Expected Result):
1.The HP Easy Start app is installed successfully.
2.The printer is in AWC mode after performing the reset.
3.The HP Easy Start app automatically selects the printer in AWC mode or finds it after clicking refresh.
4.The printer is selected, and the Wi-Fi network credentials are entered successfully. The app finds the printer.
5.The printer is authenticated and connected to the target network successfully.
6.The passive UI flow is completed successfully, and the setup is finished.
7.The Easy Start app prompts to select the software and driver, and HP Smart is selected.
8.The HP Smart app launches successfully, and print and scan operations are performed without issues.
1.The printer is discovered in the HP Easy Start app and the printer is selected.
2.The passive UI flow is completed successfully, and the setup is finished.
3.The Easy Start app prompts to select the software and driver, and HP Smart is selected.
4.The HP Smart app launches successfully, and print and scan operations are performed without issues.
Steps (Step):
1.Install the latest HP Easy Start app.
2.Ensure the printer is in AWC mode by performing a Restore Network/Factory reset or cold reset.
3.Launch the HP Easy Start app from Windows/Mac.
4.Verify that the HP Easy Start app automatically selects the printer in AWC mode. If not, click the refresh button and search for the AWC printer.
5.Select the printer from the list and enter the Wi-Fi network credentials to connect to the target network. Let the app find the printer.
6.Once the printer is found, press to authenticate is triggered. Allow the connection from the FPUI of the printer to authenticate. Wait for the device to get connected successfully to the target network.
7.Complete the passive UI flow to load the paper, install ink, and print & scan the alignment sheet to finish the setup.
8.Once the setup is done, the Easy Start app will prompt to select the software and driver and HP smart app setup.
9.Select HP Smart as recommended.
10.Once the HP Smart app is launched, perform print and scan operations from the HP Smart app.
1.Install the latest HP Easy Start app.
2.Ensure the printer is already connected to the network.
3.Launch the HP Easy Start app from Windows.
4.Select the printer which is already connected to the network using its IP address.
5.Once the printer is found, press to authenticate is triggered. Allow the connection from the FPUI of the printer to authenticate. Wait for the device to get connected successfully to the target network.
6.Complete the passive UI flow to load the paper, install ink, and print & scan the alignment sheet to finish the setup.
7.Once the setup is done, the Easy Start app will prompt to select the software and driver and HP Smart app setup.
8.Select HP Smart as recommended.
9.Once the HP Smart app is launched, perform print and scan operations from the HP Smart app.
Dependencies: HP smart client and Mobile related cannot automate

1.The printer is discovered in the HP Easy Start app and the printer is selected.
2.The passive UI flow is completed successfully, and the setup is finished.
3.The Easy Start app prompts to select the software and driver, and Full Software and Drivers is selected.

5.The driver is installed successfully, and the instructions are followed.

Steps (Step):
1.Install the latest HP Easy Start app.
2.Ensure the printer is in AWC mode by performing a Restore Network/Factory reset or cold reset.
3.Launch the HP Easy Start app from Windows.
4.Verify that the HP Easy Start app automatically selects the printer in AWC mode. If not, click the refresh button and search for the AWC printer.
5.Select the printer from the list and enter the Wi-Fi network credentials to connect to the target network. Let the app find the printer.
6.Once the printer is found, press to authenticate is triggered. Allow the connection from the FPUI of the printer to authenticate. Wait for the device to get connected successfully to the target network.
7.Complete the passive UI flow to load the paper, install ink, and print & scan the alignment sheet to finish the setup.
8.Once the setup is done, the Easy Start app will prompt to select the software and driver. Select Full Software and Drivers.
9.The Full webpack driver is downloaded.
10.Install the driver and follow the instructions.
11.Perform print and scan operations.

Title: Verify Bonjour name after backup and restore
PreConditions:
Printer is connected to a Network.
Note: Test with both interfaces Ethernet and Wi-Fi.
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > BackupRestoreImportExport
Steps (Expected Result):
Bonjour name should be restored to the value set by user verify by checking Info>Connectivity> Ethernet.
Check contents of Network Configuration Report.
Verify Bonjour name on Mac or iOS device.
Steps (Step):
1.Navgate UI to Menu>Settings>Network>Bonjour Name.
2.Edit Bonjour name. Click Apply button
3. Go to UI backup and restore option. Save backup file.
4. Perform Restore All Factory Defaults/RND.
5.Once printer comes to ready state with Connectivity,navigate to Backup and Restore option on UI and perform a Restore.
6.Verify Bonjour name EWS an UI under Network Settings and Info>Connectivity after restore.
7.Navigate to Menu>Settings>Network>Network Report> Print Network Configuration Report.

Title: IP Config method: Manual

Title: Test is to verify SNMP v1/v2 Configuration after Backup and Restore & Export and import
PreConditions:
1.Device should be connected to wired and wireless interface.
2.Test this scenario by performing both RFD and RND.
3.Test the scenario by disabling SNMPv1/v2.
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > BackupRestoreImportExport
Steps (Expected Result):
1.User should be able to configure SNMPv1/v2 setting.
2.After RFD/RND SNMPv1/v2 should reatin to its default settings i.e., SNMPv1/v2 enabled with read only access.
3.Restore : SNMPv1/v2 configuration should be restored to values which were set before.
1.Export and import operation should be successful.
2.Printer 1 settings should be import on Printer 2 successfully.
Steps (Step):
1.Launch EWS page with ipv4/ipv6 address.
2.Navigate to Network -> Network settings ->Network Services ->SNMPv1/v2
3.Configure SNMPv1/v2 with Access option, SET and GET community names.
4.Go to support tools -> Back up and Restore -> Enter password and save the backup file.
5.Perform Restore factory deafults / Restore network settings.
6.Once the device comes to ready state.
7.Goto Support tools -> Back up and restore -> Restore -> Enter the password been set -> Browse the backup file  -> Click on Restore.
1.Launch EWS page with ipv4/ipv6 address.
2.Navigate to Network -> Network settings ->Network Services ->SNMPv1/v2
3.Configure SNMPv1/v2 with Access option, SET and GET community names.
4.From FP, go to -> Tools -> Maintenance -> Export & Import -> Export the settings of Printer 1
5.Import settings on  Printer 2.
6.Check the functionality after import.

1.Perform Restore All Factory Defaults/RND.
2.Navigate UI to backup and restore option. Save backup file.
3.Navigate UI to Menu>Settings>Network> Ethernet settings > IPv4/IPv6.
4.Change IP Config method from DHCP to Manual/Auto IP.
5.Click on Apply to save changes.
6.Navigate to Backup and Restore option on UI and perform a Restore.
7.Verify Ethernet IP config settings under configuration summary.
8.Print Network Configuration report.

Title: WPS when wireless is disabled with ethernet connected
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > ET

Title: Wi-Fi icon and LED sync with the Wi-Fi radio status
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > ET
Steps (Expected Result): The Wi-Fi LED is on and start blink, Wi-Fi icon start cycling once turn on wifi.
Steps (Step):
1. Make sure Wifi is confied and on.
2. Press wifi button to turn off wifi.
3. Wait some seconds, then press wifi button to turn on wifi.(idle state)
4. Observe the LCD Wi-Fi icon on UI.

Title: Reboot the printer with wired connection if wi-fi is configured
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > ET
Steps (Expected Result): Printer boot to idle and get the iP address with Ethernet interface
Steps (Step):
1.Conect printer's Wi-Fi to AP.
2.Plug the ethernet cable.
3. Press power button to reboot the printer.
Dependencies: ethernet cable should be connected by default

Title: Restore network defaut with ethernet is connected
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > ET
Steps (Expected Result): Printer boot to idle and get the iP address with Ethernet interface
Steps (Step):
1. Turn on the printer and ensure it is idle.
2. The printer is connected to the wireless network.
3. Plug the Ethernet cable into the printer, then wireless is disabled and Ethernet icon shows on LCD.
4. From the front panel, press and hold the Info button for 3 seconds, then simultaneously press and hold the Wi-Fi button and Cancel button for 3 seconds to restore network default.
Dependencies: ethernet cable should be connected by default

Title: Verify Wireless status is connected - unplug the ethernet cable during sleep mode.
Section Hierarchy: Manual > Product_Shared > Connectivity > Wired-Connectivity > ET
Steps (Expected Result): The Wi-Fi is LED should turn on and re-connenc to Wi-Fi.
Steps (Step):
1.Conenct the printer to the wifi and then plug the ethernet cable.
2.Wait Pritner enter sleep.
3.Unplug the ethernet cable.
Dependencies: ethernet cable should be connected by default
